```
is_used = {factor: False for factor in self.factors}

        for node in clique_trees.nodes():
            clique_factors = []
            for factor in self.factors:
                # If the factor is not used in creating any clique potential as
                # well as has any variable of the given clique in its scope,
                # then use it in creating clique potential
                if not is_used[factor] and set(factor.scope()).issubset(node):
                    clique_factors.append(factor)
                    is_used[factor] = True
```
This line 
```
is_used = {factor: False for factor in self.factors}
```
should be inside the for loop as for each clique node we have to multiply by all factors whose scope is subset of variables in node. What do you guys think?

I first noticed this when I was going through Bhavana and Niket's code to run their AllenNLP dependency on Beaker.  They explicitly installed the `punkt` model, and I wasn't sure that model was necessary.  It likely isn't because, while we support a word splitter that uses the `punkt` model--we don't actually use it anywhere else in our code or in any of our models.  We also don't have tests to make sure it's working correctly (tests pass if you remove the `punkt` model).

While I prefer removing this component and dependency, the alternative for me to open and issue to write some tests for the `NltkWordSplitter`.

